<div class="vision-container glass-panel">
  <div class="vision-glow-bar"></div>
  <div class="vision-content">
    <span class="vision-tag font-mono">OUR APPROACH</span>
    <h2 class="vision-title">Why We Build Everything Ourselves</h2>

    <p class="vision-text">
      Most student rocket teams buy their flight computer. It's the pragmatic choice — a
      commercial altimeter or off-the-shelf autopilot gets you flying faster, with less risk.
      We chose the harder path instead.
    </p>

    <p class="vision-text">
      Every subsystem on this site — the power board, the sensor board, the OBC — is designed
      from scratch, in-house, by students, from schematic capture to PCB layout to firmware.
      Not because it's the fastest way to fly a rocket. Because it's the only way to actually
      <em>own</em> the engineering.
    </p>

    <p class="vision-text">
      A purchased flight computer answers one flight. A flight computer we design ourselves
      becomes a foundation — every lesson learned on Cassiopeia I's power architecture carries
      directly into Cassiopeia II. Every sensor fusion algorithm we tune this year is one we
      don't have to re-derive next year. That's the bet behind this team: that the compounding
      value of owned, reusable engineering knowledge outgrows the head start of buying it off a shelf.
    </p>

    <p class="vision-text">
      It also means every member who joins isn't operating a black box — they're extending one
      they can actually read, modify, and understand down to the register level.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

